âœ´ï¸ Fiber Optic
High-speed internet using fiber optic cables transmitting data as light signals
*ï¸âƒ£ Speed & Latency
Very high speeds (up to 1 Gbps+), low latency
*ï¸âƒ£ Key Characteristics & Use Cases
Fast, reliable, cost-effective for urban and enterprise use

âœ´ï¸ Cable Broadband
Internet over coaxial cables (cable TV infrastructure) using DOCSIS standard.
*ï¸âƒ£ Speed & Latency
Up to 1 Gbps or higher (provider-dependent)
*ï¸âƒ£ Key Characteristics & Use Cases
Shared bandwidth, widely available in urban/suburban areas.

âœ´ï¸ DSL (Digital Subscriber Line)
Internet over existing copper telephone lines, typically ADSL (asymmetric)
*ï¸âƒ£ Speed & Latency.
Up to 200 Mbps download, 20 Mbps upload; limited to ~10,000 ft from exchange.
*ï¸âƒ£ Key Characteristics & Use Cases.
Distance-limited, slower upload speeds, common in older infrastructure.

âœ´ï¸ Cellular Network
Internet via mobile networks (4G, 5G) using phones or dedicated devices
*ï¸âƒ£ Speed & Latency
Varies widely; 5G offers multi-Gbps speeds, low latency
*ï¸âƒ£ Key Characteristics & Use Cases
Mobile, supports tethering/hotspots, growing 5G adoption

âœ´ï¸ WISP (Wireless Internet Service Provider)
Internet delivered wirelessly from ground stations (not satellites) using 802.11, 5G, or proprietary tech
*ï¸âƒ£ Speed & Latency
Varies; depends on tech and environment
*ï¸âƒ£ Key Characteristics & Use Cases
Focus on rural/local wireless coverage, requires external antennas

KEY POINT
ğŸ“› Satellite: Best for remote areas but suffers from high latency and cost.
ğŸ“› Fiber: Fastest, most reliable, ideal for high-demand users.
ğŸ“› Cable: High speed but shared bandwidth can cause congestion.
ğŸ“› DSL: Limited by distance, slower upload speeds.
ğŸ“› Cellular: Mobile, flexible, with 5G promising very high speeds.
ğŸ“› WISP: Wireless alternative for rural/local areas without wired infrastructure.

